Data Analysis of the Pima Indians Diabetes Dataset using Regressions in R - Self study

Fernando Guntoro and Sonja Tang

2022-11-13

Objective: The objective of this tutorial is to investigate risk factors that are associated with diabetes in the Pima Indians Diabetes dataset using regressions.

We will put into practice basic data cleaning, linear and logistic regressions, data visualization and interpretation.

Dataset: The Pima dataset is made up of survey results from a study conducted by the National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases on female Pima Indians living near Phoenix.

Firstly, lets set up the library and load the Pima dataset from the faraway R package.

list.of.packages <- c("faraway", "viridis", "tidyverse", "corrplot")
new.packages <- list.of.packages[!(list.of.packages %in% installed.packages()[,"Package"])]
if(length(new.packages)) install.packages(new.packages)

library(faraway)
library(viridis)
library(tidyverse)
library(corrplot)
data(pima)

There are 768 individuals in the study, and 9 variables were recorded. It may be useful to categorize glucose and insulin into factors, based on some medical background (mayoclinic.org and medscape).

pima$test <- factor(pima$test)

pima$glucose_cat <- factor(ifelse(pima$glucose <= 140, "Normal",
                           ifelse(pima$glucose <= 200, "Medium", "High")))
pima$insulin_cat <- factor(ifelse(pima$insulin <= 16, "Low",
                           ifelse(pima$glucose <= 166, "Normal", "High")))

Exploratory data analysis

What are some useful types of plots for visualizing data?

Lets look at these variables in more depth by plotting a simple histogram to visualize their distributions. We can do this with base R easily, and also using ggplot.

Base R

hist(pima$age,
     main="Number of participants by age in the Pima dataset",
  xlab="Age",
  ylab="No. of people",
  col=viridis(1)
)

# Often we may want to visualize the variables altogether
par(mfrow =c(3,3))
for (i in seq(8)) {
  hist(pima[,i],
     main=names(pima)[i],
  xlab="Value",
  ylab="Frequency",
  col=viridis(1)
  )
}
par(mfrow =c(1,1))

ggplot

ggplot(pima, aes(x = age)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1, color = "black", fill = viridis(1)) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(20,90,5)) +
  ggtitle("Number of participants by age in the Pima dataset") +
  xlab("Age") +
  ylab("No of people by age") +
  theme_bw()

ggplot(gather(pima[,1:8]), aes(value)) + 
    geom_histogram(bins = 20, color = "black", fill = viridis(1)) + 
    theme_bw() +
    facet_wrap(~key, scales = 'free_x')

Further quality control check

Lets check if these variables contain any NA value, we may want to remove or impute them.

colSums(is.na(pima)) # Check if each column contains NA values
##    pregnant     glucose   diastolic     triceps     insulin         bmi 
##           0           0           0           0           0           0 
##    diabetes         age        test glucose_cat insulin_cat 
##           0           0           0           0           0

No NAs, but this was a trick question. Notice the zeros!

pima_na <- pima
pima_na$bmi[pima$bmi == 0] <- NA
pima_na$diastolic[pima$diastolic == 0] <- NA
pima_na$glucose[pima$glucose == 0] <- NA
pima_na$insulin[pima$insulin == 0] <- NA
pima_na$triceps[pima$triceps == 0] <- NA

pima_na <- na.omit(pima_na) # remove all observations containing NA values

Now that we have removed the NAs, lets visualize the distributions again.

Base R plot

Linear Regression

We can use glm to fit generalized linear models. We need to give it minimally two objects: (1) a formula specifying the model, and (2) the error distribution. The formula is constructed using y ~ x, whereas the error distribution is by default gaussian but can be switched to binomial, poisson, etc as appropriate. For more arguments see ?glm. Also

1 continuous predictor

fit1.cont <- glm(bmi ~ glucose, data =pima)
summary(fit1.cont)

Checking model performance

Visualizing model properties and assumptions

par(mfrow=c(2,2)) ## show 2 by 2 plot
plot(fit1.cont)

par(mfrow=c(1,1))   ## reset to show 1 plot at a time

Residuals vs Fitted inspects if there is curvilinear trend; residuals should be randomly distributed around zero.

Normal Q-Q inspects if your residuals are normally distributed i.e.should be dotted around diagonal line

Scale-Location similar to Residuals vs Fitted; help identify heteroskedasticity

Residuals vs Leveragedetects outliers.

Running one-way ANOVA

fit.aov <- aov(fit1.cont)
summary(fit.aov)
##              Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)    
## glucose       1   2330  2330.1   39.36 5.89e-10 ***

## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Comparing two models

To compare the fit between two models, you can use anova. It takes two model objects as argument, and returns an ANOVA test suggesting whether one model is significantly better than another.

# ANOVA
anova(fit1.cont, fit2.cont, test="Chi")

Example

What is the difference in the log-odds of testing positive for diabetes for a woman with a glucose level at the first quartile compared with a woman at the third quartile, assuming that all other factors are held constant? Then calculate the associated odds ratio value, and give a 95% confidence interval for this odds ratio.

summary(pima_na$glucose)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    56.0    99.0   119.0   122.6   143.0   198.0
fit.summary <- summary(fit.all)
fit.summary
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = test ~ ., family = binomial, data = pima[1:9])
## 
## Deviance Residuals: 
##     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max  
## -2.5566  -0.7274  -0.4159   0.7267   2.9297  
## 
## Coefficients:
##               Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)    
## (Intercept) -8.4046964  0.7166359 -11.728  < 2e-16 ***
## pregnant     0.1231823  0.0320776   3.840 0.000123 ***
## glucose      0.0351637  0.0037087   9.481  < 2e-16 ***
## diastolic   -0.0132955  0.0052336  -2.540 0.011072 *  
## triceps      0.0006190  0.0068994   0.090 0.928515    
## insulin     -0.0011917  0.0009012  -1.322 0.186065    
## bmi          0.0897010  0.0150876   5.945 2.76e-09 ***
## diabetes     0.9451797  0.2991475   3.160 0.001580 ** 
## age          0.0148690  0.0093348   1.593 0.111192    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## (Dispersion parameter for binomial family taken to be 1)
## 
##     Null deviance: 993.48  on 767  degrees of freedom
## Residual deviance: 723.45  on 759  degrees of freedom
## AIC: 741.45
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 5
# Log-odds difference
LO <- coef(fit.all)["glucose"]
quart_1 <- quantile(pima_na$glucose, 0.25) # summary(pima_na$glucose)[2]
quart_3 <-  quantile(pima_na$glucose, 0.75) 

diff = LO * (quart_3 - quart_1)

# Estimated log-odds ratio
exp(diff)
##  glucose 
## 4.698313
# 95% conf int for odds ratio
conf_int_odds <- cbind(diff - 1.96*fit.summary$coefficients[3,2] * (quart_3 - quart_1),
                       diff + 1.96*fit.summary$coefficients[3,2] * (quart_3 - quart_1))

# 95% conf int for estimated odds ratio
exp(conf_int_odds)
##             [,1]     [,2]
